<p>Retailers had a busy summer. While the Paris Olympics and EURO 2024 took consumer attention by storm, UK retailers spent the last couple of months preparing for a climactic year-end, integrating new technologies to boost new sales channels, put customers at the center of their strategies, and strengthen their brick-and-mortar presence. Here's a look at some of the most notable stories to come out of UK retail in July and August.</p>

<h2>Striving for exciting experiences</h2>
<p>Customers remain at the heart of retail operations, and several retailers spent the past few months adopting more customer-centric strategies designed to exceed expectations at every touchpoint. British retailer Pets at Home unveiled the first of four planned concept stores, fitted with digital and interactive features to guide customers through their pet care journeys, reflecting the brand's commitment to experience going forward. Plush toy brand Jellycat delivered its own creative store moment with an interactive pop-up at Selfridges London in late July, celebrating the launch of its "Fish & Chips" collection for its 25th anniversary. The exclusive experience let customers book slots to visit the pop-up and take part in ordering their soft toys, inspired by the famous British dish. Pop-up and concept flagship stores are becoming a significant part of how retailers are reshaping their relationship with consumers.</p>

<h2>Blending operations</h2>
<p>Home and leisure retailer The Range made headlines going live with new iOS and Android apps, making online ordering easier and giving customers access to thousands of products through an entirely new sales channel. Electrical retailer Currys, meanwhile, set its sights on a blended in-store and online omnichannel model, with 50 of its biggest stores getting a makeover that includes new categories, seasonal showcases, and reimagined in-store merchandising. That follows an earlier announcement to redesign 65 store layouts, part of a plan to transform 115 of Currys's 305 UK stores across 2024 and 2025, all aimed at enhancing the customer experience.</p>
<p>Online marketplace eBay, official sponsor of ITV's Love Island, capitalized on the show's success this summer, which saw 2.2 million people tune into the first episode, its highest since 2022. eBay hosted the first-ever Love Island eBay Live, a live shopping event showcasing pre-loved fashion items from iconic moments in the show's history, giving fans a new, interactive way to shop.</p>

<h2>Developing relationships</h2>
<p>As the British summer's unpredictable weather kept everyone on their toes, one constant trend held: retailers continuing to strengthen partnerships for the benefit of the end customer. Fashion giant ASOS extended its relationship with Microsoft, signing a three-year agreement to expand its use of generative AI, aiming to operate more efficiently while rolling out AI tools that enhance the customer experience. AI in retail has quickly gone from an exciting promise to a real deployment, and it's a space worth watching closely as the technology matures.</p>

<h2>Heading into the change of seasons</h2>
<p>July and August made clear that customer experience continues to drive innovation and strategy, with an emphasis on blending operations and thinking beyond the traditional store format. As the year moves forward and festive shopping season approaches, that focus on perfecting the customer experience is only going to intensify.</p>
